<HEADLINE>
FT  18 NOV 94 / Thatcher takes up arms of war
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Baroness Thatcher's coat of arms, with the Falklands war a central theme,
was unveiled yesterday.
The former prime minister is said to be delighted with the creation by Sir
Colin Cole, the retired Garter King of Arms. Sir Colin said it symbolised
Lady Thatcher's 'sentiments, career and achievements'.
The Falklands victory is depicted by the figure of an admiral on active
service. A representation of Sir Isaac Newton, who came from the the same
area as Lady Thatcher - Grantham, Lincolnshire - symbolises her abiding
interest in science.
The motto 'Cherish Freedom' was chosen by Lady Thatcher as being 'short and
appropriate'. The coronet with four pearls is the traditional heraldic
symbol for a baron or baroness. The lions, representing patriotism, are
supporting a double key, which alludes to the double office of prime
minister and First Lord of the Treasury. The tower and portcullis represent
the Palace of Westminster and the cross beneath, the Order of Merit.
</TEXT>
