<HEADLINE>
FT  18 NOV 94 / Vocational training project launched
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
General vocational quali-fications for 14-year-olds will be piloted in
English and Welsh schools next year, with an assessment system which has
been radically altered in response to attacks from inspectors.
Schools already experienced in vocational education have been asked to
tender for pilot courses in three subjects - business and finance, health
and social care, and manufacturing - from September next year.
Ministers want to pilot more courses in 1996 including leisure and tourism,
art and design and science. They also want to expand to include schools with
little experience of teaching vocational courses. If all goes well, the
courses, to be known as General National Vocational Qualification (GNVQ)
Part Ones, will be offered to all secondary schools from September 1998.
Each GNVQ will be equal to two GCSEs.
The education and employment departments have worked jointly on the
syllabuses for the new courses, following proposals made in January by Sir
Ron Dearing, the chief government curriculum adviser.
Sir Ron attacked claims that vocational qualifications would be viewed as
second-rate. He said: 'I think that's a traditional view and it's a national
tragedy. We've suffered grievously from that value structure, and our
competitors have not.' He said the new courses would be attractive to the
most academically able pupils.
The system for assessing the qualifications has been overhauled after
criticism from Ofsted - the government's education inspectorate - of last
year's pilot scheme for GNVQs for sixth-formers.
The inspectors said GNVQs needed tougher external checks. The qualifications
made insufficient attempts to grade students and merely checked whether
students had achieved a basic competence.
Under the new arrangements for GNVQ Part Ones, students must prove their
competence by gaining at least 70 per cent in multiple choice 'mastery
tests'. These can be taken at three times during the year, and are included
at the request of employers.
Students must also produce a portfolio of work to show that they have
satisfied various performance criteria. In practice this will require
extensive work experience with local employers. They cannot, however, win
'merit' or 'distinction' marks without taking further external extension
tests, designed to assess the depth of their knowledge.
Controlled assignments have been added to GNVQs for the first time. Pupils
must undertake tasks set by the bodies awarding the qualifications, under
the supervision of a teacher. They will be marked by both the teacher and
the awarding body's assessors.
Ofsted said these developments answered its criticisms on standards and
external checks. Both innovations are likely to be adopted for advanced
GNVQs if the pilot is successful.
Students will be barred from passing their GNVQ if their coursework for
academic GCSEs does not demonstrate mastery of the core skills of literacy,
numeracy and use of information technology.
The Confederation of British Industry welcomed the proposals, saying they
had the potential to 'transform the learning of young people'. It said that
teaching staff in the pilot schools should receive extra training, and that
they should have established links with employers.
Teachers' unions welcomed the initiative, but insisted that they should be
properly resourced with 'appropriate in-service training'.
Labour was more guarded. Mr David Blunkett, shadow education secretary,
said: 'There is a very real danger that we will end up with a two-tier
qualification system if we don't ensure that GNVQs are seen alongside GCSEs
as of potentially equal esteem.'
</TEXT>
<XX>
