<HEADLINE>
FT  18 NOV 94 / Welsh power pay deal accepted
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR, Employment Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Trade unions at South Wales Electricity have negotiated a wage agreement
that will reduce pay levels for workers who join the company after December
5.
The deal will extend performance-related pay or annual appraisals for wage
increases to all the company's existing employees from April. The pay of
existing workers will be protected.
Existing staff will receive a 5.9 per cent backdated increase, made up of
2.9 per cent for last year and 3 per cent for this year, as well as lump sum
one-off payments ranging from Pounds 350 to Pounds 1,250 to buy out
allowances.
Mr Andrew Walker, the group's chief executive, said: 'I consider the new
agreement is at the forefront of deals across the electricity industry.
'We have placed great importance during the negotiations on improving
employee flexibility and cost effectiveness.'
The company insisted that there should be market related pay scales for all
new recruits to ensure greater flexibility.
Employees have accepted a range of new working practices under the deal.
These include the introduction of flexible working hours for everybody, with
an average 37 hours a week.
A single pay structure is to replace the three-tier wage scale and single
table bar-gaining is to be introduced for all five unions in the company.
The agreement will introduce monthly credit transfer for paying all workers
and extend maternity leave to 14 weeks on full pay.
The agreement guarantees a role for the trade unions.
The company said it would recognise the 'full value of collective bargaining
arrangements' for which their 'support and commitment' were necessary.
</TEXT>
