<HEADLINE>
FT  18 NOV 94 / PIA to go ahead on advice guidelines
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Financial regulators are pressing ahead with plans to inform customers of
whether any financial advice they receive is independent, in spite of
resistance from banks and building societies.
From next May, financial organisations will have to make clear to consumers
whether they provide independent advice or advice only on a particular
company's products.
The Personal Investment Authority, the retail investors' watchdog, yesterday
outlined rules saying that the type of advice given by each of its members
should be disclosed by signs in branches and in marketing material.
The PIA also says the disclosure requirements should apply to broadcast as
well as printed advertisements for mortgages, unless the material refers
only to repayment mortgages.
Most banks and large building societies have their own life insurance
subsidiaries or are linked with a single life insurer, and so do not provide
advice about products from a range of companies.
Of the large high street financial institutions, only Bradford &amp; Bingley
Building Society and Yorkshire Building Society offer solely independent
advice.
</TEXT>
