<HEADLINE>
FT  18 NOV 94 / Mortgage benefit cuts to be limited
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BLITZ and ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Kenneth Clarke, the chancellor, will try to consolidate the housing
market's fragile recovery in this month's Budget by introducing only limited
cuts in mortgage benefit payments to people on low incomes.
He is, however, expected to signal that there will be further cuts in the
amount of mortgage interest relief to recipients of income support,
encouraging householders to take out private insurance in future years.
As the government prepares to cut about Pounds 5bn from its public spending
bill in this year's Budget, the chancellor is expected to announce a
reduction in the ceiling for which mortgage benefit can be paid from Pounds
125,000 to Pounds 100,000.
This is a smaller reduction than had been expected by mortgage lenders, who
had assumed that the top limit would be set at Pounds 90,000.
Treasury officials have accepted an argument from Mr Peter Lilley, the
social security secretary, that a reduction of the ceiling to this lower
level would hit the broad mass of mortgage holders and could amount to
another serious setback for the housing market.
Ministers believe that it would be politically difficult to implement
drastic reductions in the mortgage benefit system, which costs taxpayers
about Pounds 1.2bn per year. They have also said that they will shy away
from announcing projected cuts for future years in this month's Budget.
They have, however, made no secret of their long-term desire to phase out
the system, arguing that it is difficult to operate because of constant
changes in the level of interest repayments.
As one official put it: 'It is unlikely we will set a target for the future.
But we are sending out pretty strong signals that people should not rely on
this form of support for ever. We'd be very keen on people taking out
private insurance.'
Earlier this month the Council of Mortgage Lenders warned that a cut in the
top limit for relief to Pounds 90,000 would mean that more than 200,000
mortgage-holders would run a greater risk of having their homes repossessed.
This would affect almost twice as many mortgage-holders as would be the case
if the ceiling were reduced to Pounds 100,000. The CML, which represents
banks, building societies and other lenders, is opposed even to this smaller
change.
Although the number of properties repossessed has been falling in the past
couple of years, repossessions are still at historically very high levels.
</TEXT>
