links with House of Fraser, the one-time owner of Harrods.
Sir Peter Hordern, MP for Horsham, is set to be replaced by Sir Donald
Thompson, Tory MP for Calder Valley, a former junior agriculture minister.
Sir Peter, who acted as a consultant to House of Fraser for most of the
1980s, said yesterday he had no connection with Mr Mohamed Fayed, the
present owner of Harrods, whose allegations about payments to MPs have
damaged the government.
Sir Donald lists a range of paid adviserships and consultancies in the most
recent register of MPs' interests.
These include: adviser to the National Federation of Meat Traders, adviser
to the British Agrochemicals Association, adviser to the National Caravan
Council, and adviser to Catering Equipment Manufacturers and Suppliers.
The cash for questions investigation has been thrown into confusion by Mr
Tony Benn, the veteran Labour leftwinger. Earlier this month he defied
parliamentary rules by publishing details of its private deliberations.
Calls for Mr Benn's expulsion from the committee may be discussed when it
next meets on November 21.
The committee is also to look into The Guardian's use of a fake fax to
investigate a stay by Mr Jonathan Aitken, chief Treasury secretary, at the
Paris Ritz hotel.
Mr Peter Preston, The Guardian's editor, has admitted using the House of
Commons logo on a letter sent to the Ritz, in which details of Mr Aitken's
bill were requested.
