<HEADLINE>
FT  18 NOV 94 / EU telecoms deadline set
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BRUSSELS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
EU member states last night set a clear deadline of January 1 1998 for
liberalising telecommunications infrastructures. In a move which should
sharply lower prices in Europe's highly regulated telecoms sector, industry
ministers agreed to open up all networks to competition within three years.
Ireland, Spain, Portugal and Greece can delay by a further five years if
they choose. The move will allow companies offering telecom services a much
greater choice of network provider and the right to build their own
infrastructures.
The decision fell well short of Commission ambitions to press ahead with
liberalisation of infrastructures next year, however. And at the end of the
meeting advocates of swifter deregulation - Germany, France, the
Netherlands, Sweden, Finland and Britain - issued a statement urging
Brussels to 'come forward as quickly as possible with proposals' to
liberalise the alternative networks such as cable TV, road, rail and energy
networks.
Mr Karel Van Miert, competition commissioner, is considering using special
powers that would allow him to force open cable TV networks to competition,
without a vote from the council of ministers.
US telecoms promise, Page 7
