<HEADLINE>
FT  18 NOV 94 / France plans initiative on pensions reform
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN RIDDING
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Edmond Alphandery, the French economy minister, yesterday relaunched
plans to encourage private pension funds in France, announcing that a reform
of the country's pension system should be implemented next year.
'Conditions should be right for an initiative in 1995,' Mr Alphandery said
in a speech to members of the COB, the French stock market regulator.
The development of capitalised pension funds is seen as an important means
of reducing pressure on the existing 'pay-as-you-go' system and curbing the
French welfare deficit. But reforms have been delayed by the political
sensitivity of the issue and the complexity of reform.
The current system, in which pensions are paid from contributions from the
existing workforce, suffered a deficit of more than FFr40bn (Pounds 4.75bn)
last year and faces increased strains because of the country's ageing
population.
Mr Alphandery also regards private pension funds as a way of strengthening
France's financial markets and increasing long-term savings. 'Since this
government took office it has sought to shift short-term savings to the
medium or long term,' he said.
Measures to encourage the formation of private pension funds, originally
slated for this year, have been delayed by several factors. The reform of
the pensions system is politically sensitive and has been opposed by some
trade unions.
'The existing system is a source of solidarity between age groups and social
classes,' said an official at Force Ouvriere, one of France's largest
unions. 'Incentives for private schemes will favour the wealthy and will
harm the economy by reducing consumption.'
Reform has also been complicated by divergences between reform proposals and
disputes between companies seeking to participate in capitalised pension
schemes. The Patronat employers' federation, the Association of French banks
and Mr Jacques Barrot, chairman of the National Assembly's finance
committee, have all drawn up separate projects. Insurance companies and
banks have been at odds over whether retirement payments should be made in
lump sumps, which the banks favour, or in the form of annuities.
Industry observers said yesterday that the political sensitivity and
complexity of the issue meant reform was unlikely before next spring's
presidential election.
'I don't think we will see a text for a reform for the next few months,'
said one French merchant banker.
</TEXT>
