<HEADLINE>
FT  18 NOV 94 / Retailers fear tough Christmas as rise in sales slows
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By GILLIAN TETT, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Trading conditions for Britain's shops in the crucial pre-Christmas period
will be tough, retailers warned yesterday.
Although official figures showed that retail sales in October were higher
than last year, the rate of growth has slowed in recent months and price
competition remains intense.
The Central Statistical Office said retail sales volumes in October were a
seasonally adjusted 0.1 per cent higher than in September. Year on year
growth slowed to 3.1 per cent in October, from 3.5 per cent in September.
On a three-month basis, a more accurate indication of trends, sales volumes
were 0.6 per cent higher than over the three months to July, a slightly
slower rate of growth than in previous months.
Highlighting the fierce price competition in the high street, the value of
retail sales rose only 0.7 per cent on a seasonally adjusted basis in the
three months to October, compared with the previous three months.
Adding to the picture of subdued retail activity, Bank of England figures
showed yesterday that the annual growth rate of notes and coins in
circulation in the past week stood at 5.8 per cent, the lowest since
mid-July.
The combination of slack consumer demand and low inflation will be welcomed
by the government as it prepares for the Budget on November 29.
Officials believe economic growth is now 're-balancing' from consumer demand
towards an industry-based recovery.
The figures disappointed retailers. Mr James May, director general of the
British Retail Consortium, said: 'We now expect Christmas trading to be
tough, with consumers spending wisely and carefully, but achieving levels
slightly ahead of last year.'
Small retailers squeezed, Page 11
</TEXT>
