<HEADLINE>
FT  17 NOV 94 / International Company News: Regulator says no to BA-Qantas
co-operation
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   SYDNEY
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The Australian Trade Practices Commission, the country's competition
watchdog, has barred British Airways and Qantas, the Australian carrier,
from pooling resources on their Australia-to-Europe routes.
In a draft ruling, the TPC said that the carriers were seeking authorisation
of a wide-ranging open-ended agreement with detrimental anti-competitive
effects, given that their combined market share on the routes was around 50
per cent.
The two carriers announced earlier this year that they wanted to co-operate
on the so-called 'Kangaroo' routes, but the move brought strong protests
from consumer organisations and some rival airlines. They feared that a
BA-Qantas agreement could herald higher prices and less competition.
The move would have been the first significant operational change since
British Airways became a minority shareholder in Qantas last year, acquiring
a 25 per cent interest in the government-owned airline for ADollars 665m
(USDollars 500m). It would have meant the end to around 50 years of
competition on the Kangaroo routes, and the pooling of more than ADollars
1bn of annual revenues.
Qantas argued that the move would allow cost savings estimated to be worth
tens of millions of dollars. The routes, although a significant part of
Qantas' business accounting for about 25 per cent of its international
capacity, have not been a big money-earner.
Under the proposals, the two carriers would have split profits and revenue
on the route from Australia through Singapore or Bangkok to Europe. Qantas
would have cut services between Perth and Singapore from twice daily to
once. BA would have made up this capacity loss, but would have pulled out of
services to Adelaide.
The TPC ruling has important political implications, given the Australian
government's decision to float its remaining 75 per cent stake in Qantas
early next year.
The government has already shown it is willing to protect Qantas' short-term
profitability, by rescinding an agreement with New Zealand that would have
allowed Air New Zealand to fly Australian domestic routes. That decision
caused a political row between the two countries.
Legislation which could give more time for the flotation of the state's 75
per cent stake in Qantas was introduced yesterday. The bill extends a
deadline of June 30 next year for the share offering, to the end of August.
</TEXT>
