<HEADLINE>
FT  17 NOV 94 / International Company News: Exxon signs Indonesian natural
gas field accord
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PATRICK HARVERSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Exxon, the US energy group, announced yesterday it had finally reached
agreement with the Indonesian government to develop the largest natural gas
field in south-east Asia, the Natuna field in the South China Sea.
Exxon will share the development costs with Pertamina, the state-owned
Indonesian oil and gas company.
Natuna will be the largest natural gas development project undertaken by
Exxon.
If demand for gas in the Asia-Pacific region is strong enough, it could
involve the group spending as much as Dollars 40bn over the next 30 years.
However, analysts believe the cash-strapped Pertamina will be unable to fund
its share of the development costs, and that a third partner - possibly
Mobil of the US - will be asked to join the project.
Mobil said yesterday that it would be pleased to be invited to join the the
Natuna development, but it had not been approached by either Pertamina or
Exxon.
Before construction and engineering work begins, Exxon must secure market
outlets for the gas product. It will immediately start marketing the gas to
Japan, North and South Korea, Taiwan and other countries in the region.
The level of demand will determine the scale of the development, said Exxon,
which estimates that production will not begin until after 2000.
For Indonesia, the signing of the contract between Pertamina and Exxon
should ensure that the country remains the world's largest exporter of
liquefied natural gas over the next few decades.
In recent years, production at other Indonesian gas fields has begun to
decline, and a report by the World Bank last year attached 'critical
importance' to the development of the Natuna field for the future of the
country's natural gas industry.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Companies:-
</XX>
<CO>Exxon Corp.
    Pertamina.
</CO>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>IDZ  Indonesia, Asia.
