<HEADLINE>
FT  17 NOV 94 / International Company News: Mixed reaction to Renault offer
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN RIDDING
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   PARIS
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The partial privatisation of Renault, the French motor group, enjoyed strong
demand from the company's workforce and institutional investors, but was
less enthusiastically received by the public.
Mr Edmond Alphandery, the economy minister, announced yesterday that the
public offer drew 1.09m private investors and was 1.4 times subscribed. The
number of investors was less than previous issues in the French government's
privatisation programme, which have attracted between 1.9m and 3m
subscribers.
The partial privatisation is part of the government's plan to sell 21
publicly-owned companies. Renault's flotation will bring in just under
FFr8bn (Dollars 1.5bn), taking proceeds from the sale of public sector
assets to FFr60bn for the year, compared with a target of FFr55bn. 'Our
mission is accomplished,' said Mr Alphandery.
Mr Alphandery said comparisons with previous issues were misleading because
the state was retaining control of Renault with a stake of just over 50 per
cent. 'It was a partial privatisation, which tends to limit investors'
interest,' he said. Industry analysts added that demand from private
investors was limited by the weakness of the Paris stock market and the fact
that most privatisation stocks have fallen below their issue price.
Given such considerations, Mr Alphandery said that the operation was
'particularly satisfying'.
He said the institutional tranche of the issue was 15.5 times subscribed and
Renault's employees had shown strong demand for shares. The offer for
employees closed last night, but about 60 per cent of the workforce have
applied for shares.
Mr Alphandery declined to be drawn on whether there would be more asset
sales this year. Assurances Generales de France, the insurer, is prepared
for privatisation, but the operation is awaiting improved stock market
conditions. The government is to invite offers from industrial groups
seeking to participate in the privatisation of Groupe Bull, the loss-making
computer manufacturer.
Renault shares, which will be listed on the Paris stock market today, saw
healthy demand on the grey market yesterday, trading at more than FFr10
above the FFr165 paid by private investors.
</TEXT>
