<HEADLINE>
FT  17 NOV 94 / UK Company News: Asprey statement seeks to reassure
investors
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT PESTON and WILLIAM LEWIS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Asprey, the Queen's jeweller, is today expected to issue a joint statement
with its bankers, the Bank of Scotland, in an attempt to reassure investors
that its financial health is not in jeopardy.
It also emerged last night that the Stock Exchange's surveillance
department, which investigates possible wrongdoing in share dealings, has
been examining events at Asprey.
In its statement today, the bank will confirm that the contents of a leaked
memorandum from its UK banking division, which expresses concern about
Asprey's financial condition, is genuine.
But it will say that the date of the memorandum, which was first disclosed
in last weekend's Mail on Sunday, was September - and not October 28, as
appears on the leaked copies.
A banker said last night that he regarded it as 'highly significant' that
the date had been altered on the leaked memorandum.
Since the memorandum was drafted by Mr Richard Ramsey, the bank's director
of structured finance, the bank has satisfied itself that Asprey is trading
in accordance with the terms of the Pounds 20m banking facility, which it
provided to the group on June 29.
Asprey's shares have plunged to 148p from a year's high of 357p.
Most of the price collapse came in September, when the group announced that
it would be only 'marginally profitable' in the first half of the financial
year and that profits in the full year would be 'well below current market
expectations'.
In the memorandum, Mr Ramsey says: 'It is possible that the directors (of
Asprey) were not wholly open with us at the time of signing (of the loan
facility) with regard to the achievement of the budgeted level of profit'.
However, a banker said this was a view intended for discussion by internal
executives only and did not represent the board's opinion.
In the previous year, Asprey made pre-tax profits of Pounds 25.4m. Its
accounts for this year were signed and approved by directors and auditors on
July 6.
In the preface to the accounts, Mr John Asprey, the group's chairman, says:
'After a world recession . . . we are encouraged by signs of improvement . .
. We expect to benefit from a recovery in the economic climate, although the
rate of that recovery remains uncertain.'
On July 8, Namara, a company in which Mr Naim Attallah, Asprey's chief
executive, has a controlling interest, sold its holding of 415,375 Asprey
shares at a price of 306p.
Namara had bought 250,000 of these from Mr Attallah the previous September,
at a price of 317.5p.
On July 14, Mr Attallah and another Asprey director, Mr Nicholas Harrington,
sold a further 54,127 shares and 30,836 shares respectively, at a price of
310p.
These shares had been acquired three days earlier following the exercise of
share options at a price of 268p.
At around the same time, Asprey's employee benefit fund spent Pounds 774,110
on purchases of Asprey shares. On July 8, it bought 40,375 shares at 306p
and on July 14 it bought 209,859 shares.
Asprey has indicated that the collapse in profits was due to a large extent
to the loss of sales to a particular middle eastern client, believed to be
the Sultan of Oman. However, a sharp fall in profits of its main Bond Street
showroom in London, responsible for most business with such clients, was
already discounted in its budget for the current year.
There was a bigger drop compared with budget in the profits expected to be
earned by a series of subsidiaries, Watches of Switzerland, Garrard and Les
Ambassadeurs.
</TEXT>
