<HEADLINE>
FT  17 NOV 94 / Union Carbide and Mitsubishi sell joint venture for Dollars
1.1bn
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By TONY JACKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
Union Carbide of the US and Mitsubishi of Japan are to sell UCAR, their
jointly-owned graphite electrodes business, to the New York investment group
Blackstone in a deal valuing it at Dollars 1.1bn. Union Carbide will retain
a 25 per cent holding.
UCAR is the world's biggest maker of graphite and carbon electrodes, used in
steelmaking. Sales last year were Dollars 770m.
The deal values UCAR's equity at Dollars 820m, and Blackstone will also
assume debt of around Dollars 190m. This replaces the planned flotation of
around 44 per cent of UCAR announced last month.
Union Carbide will receive Dollars 347m, resulting in a significant capital
gain, the company said. Mitsubishi, which bought a half share in UCAR in
1991, will receive Dollars 406m for its entire holding. Mitsubishi said this
would result in a profit of Y17.6bn (Pounds 113m) over book value.
Union Carbide said the sale effectively completed a programme of disposals
begun in 1991, designed to return the group to its core activities in
chemicals and plastics.
At the time, the group said it aimed to realise Dollars 500m from the sale
of non-strategic assets. The target was reached last year with the Dollars
300m disposal of its organosilicon business, OSI Specialties. The company
has also spun off its industrial gases subsidiary.
It is understood that the flotation plan was shelved because Blackstone
offered a higher price. It is also believed that Mitsubishi decided to sell
out because it was reluctant to hold a minority position. The company was
not available for comment.
Mr Stephen Schwarzman, president and chief executive of Blackstone, said the
equity investment in the buy-out would be Dollars 250m, with 75 per cent
supplied by his firm and 25 per cent by Union Carbide.
A particular attraction of the deal, he said, was that UCAR's products are
used particularly in the fast-growing mini-mill sector of the steel
industry, which is little affected by recession.
The total cost of the transaction, including fees and overseas taxes, would
be approximately Dollars 1.2bn, Mr Schwarzman said. Of that, Dollars 950m
would be funded by debt and Dollars 250m by equity. Close to Dollars 200m of
the equity would be put in by Blackstone with the remainder coming from
Union Carbide.
In addition, he said, two-thirds of UCAR's sales are outside the US.
'We think that as Europe comes out of recession, we'll get the benefit of
exposure there', he said.
Mr Schwarzman added that UCAR could be floated publicly within the next year
or two.
</TEXT>
