<HEADLINE>
FT  17 NOV 94 / Brussels officials clash on state aid to airlines
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LIONEL BARBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   STRASBOURG
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
A fragile consensus inside the European Commission snapped yesterday as two
senior commissioners disagreed in public over newly agreed guidelines on
state aid to Europe's troubled airlines.
The rift emerged after Mr Marcelino Oreja, outgoing Spanish transport
commissioner, suggested that state bail-outs could be justified in
exceptional circumstances, such as currency devaluations or a war.
Mr Karel Van Miert, Belgian commissioner responsible for competition policy,
rejected Mr Oreja's statement on currency devaluations as incompatible with
guidelines agreed hours earlier by the full 17-member Commission. 'This is
not a correct interpretation,' he said.
The clash raises questions about the credibility of the guidelines, which
are intended to serve as justification for the recent approval of FFr20bn
(Pounds 2.4bn) in state aid to Air France and as a reference for future aid
cases.
Consideration of currency devaluations in state aid cases would be highly
controversial. It would favour airlines from countries with weaker
currencies, such as Olympic of Greece.
The debate about the tightness with which rules on state aid should be drawn
has intensified in Europe after British Airways and other European airlines
in the private sector mounted a legal challenge to the Commission's decision
last summer to approve the Air France aid.
Yesterday's clash represented a dress rehearsal for the battle in Brussels
over whether to approve new state aid for Iberia, the Spanish national
carrier, which may seek up to Dollars 1bn as part of a new restructuring
package.
Spanish officials are privately furious that Mr Van Miert pre-emptively
ruled out a new state aid package for Iberia last week - ahead of any such
request.
This week, Mr Van Miert succeeded in strengthening the eight new Commission
guidelines on state aid. In future, airlines may expect Commission approval
only 'under exceptional circumstances, unforeseeable and external to the
company'.
A Brussels official explained that the new version was in line with the 'one
time, last time' policy on state aid which underpins efforts in Brussels to
liberalise the airline industry by 1997. 'Exceptional and unforeseeable
circumstances means earthquakes or a stock market collapse,' the official
explained.
Mr Oreja told a news conference in Strasbourg that the Treaty of Rome
clearly provided for state aid, adding assistance could be justified if it
was vital to restore the airline to financial viability and resulted from
'circumstances beyond the company's control' - including war or sudden
currency devaluation.
Mr Oreja predicted that the Commission would become progressively tougher on
applications for state aid as competition increased in the wake of further
air transport liberalisation in 1997.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>QRZ  European Economic Community (EC).
    FRZ  France, EC.
</CN>
