<HEADLINE>
FT  17 NOV 94 / Observer: Prime timing
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
Not a peep so far from Canada's Big Five banks. When US banks lift their
prime lending rates, as they have this week, their Canadian counterparts
aren't usually backward in coming forward.
Bank economists can find any number of technical reasons, mostly to do with
interest-rate spreads, why the Canadian banks won't be following suit just
yet.
But Observer's not fooled. The banks' year ended on October 31 and their
reporting season begins next Tuesday. Several are expected to announce
record profits. Royal Bank of Canada, for instance, is set to become the
first Canadian bank to earn more than CDollars 1bn.
Having long struggled to overcome a reputation as corporate fat cats, the
last thing the banks want is to be seen, through a rise in the cost of
lending, to be upsetting the small businessmen they are keen to woo.
But . . . once the results season is over, the profit motive is sure to come
back into its own.
</TEXT>
