<HEADLINE>
FT  17 NOV 94 / Arts: Today's Television
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN HOYLE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
What constitutes a riot? Tonight's revelation of Forbidden Britain (9.45pm,
BBC2) is too vague, including Orange march scuffles, striking miners and the
1946 Bolton football disaster when 33 were crushed to death. But riots? You
might as well include Harrod's sale.
Despite Zoe Wanamaker's portentous tones claiming that riot coverage has
always been censored, there's plenty of the real thing, notably a 1932
hunger march that turned violent and the battle of Cable Street. Wry
recollections never fulfil the subtitle's promise, 'Our Secret Past'.
Finney (9pm, ITV), a new drama series hovering dangerously near cliche, is
worth a look for the acting. Warm-hearted Geordies have a criminal
underworld and gangster sub-culture that can turn nasty to the family white
sheep (David Morrissey).
Family ties of a different kind are infinitely moving in Witness: The Search
for Alison MacDonald (9pm, C4). The mystery is less what happened to Alison
when she vanished in India but why her father, a Scottish minister, is
convinced of both her survival and God's goodness.
