<DOCNO>FT944-9025</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-EKQEIADMFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>941117
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  17 NOV 94 / The Queen's Speech: Contentious clauses may evade debate -
Pensions reform
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NORMA COHEN, Investments Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government's intention to introduce sweeping legislation to bring sex
equality into state pensions and 'security, equality and choice' into
occupational and personal pensions was announced in a single sentence.
But the bill is likely to be one of the biggest introduced into parliament
in recent years. The pensions industry expects it to include up to 140
clauses and to take until next autumn to become law.
Industry officials are saying that some of the most contentious parts of the
legislation - setting out how it is to be applied - may not be debated
during the bill's passage through parliament, but instead be covered by
secondary legislation, regulations from the Department of Social Security or
'guidance notes' from the Institute and Faculty of Actuaries, a
non-governmental professional body.
Mr Frank Field, Labour chairman of the Commons social security committee,
expressed concern yesterday that some crucial provisions, such as minimum
solvency, would not be subject to political debate. Mr Field said the
government could issue statutory instruments in advance so that MPs could
know exactly how it intended to apply vague provisions of the legislation.
In particular, the bill may not include the specifics of a new 'minimum
solvency requirement' which will require pension schemes to have enough
assets to pay accrued pension benefits if they are wound up immediately. How
the value of those assets is to be calculated is the subject of acrimonious
debate, with employers saying the plans will impose significant costs on
schemes.
Actuaries are questioning whether a lower-cost alternative being considered
will go far enough to offer the security recommended by the government's
advisory body, the Pension Law Review Committee.
Ms Penny Webster, partner at consulting actuaries Bacon and Woodrow, said:
'My concern is that, depending on what solution is adopted, it could be
misleading.'
The main points of the legislation are:
To raise the age at which women are eligible to receive state pension
payments to 65 to match that of men.
To give effect in domestic legislation to recent rulings from the European
Court of Justice requiring employers to offer equal pension benefits to men
and women.
To simplify arrangements for contracting out of the State Earnings Related
Pension Scheme, including abolishing the alternative Guaranteed Minimum
Pension. Instead, employers will have to demonstrate that they offer
benefits broadly equal to those obtainable under Serps to be eligible to
receive rebates of National Insurance contributions.
To require all occupational and personal pensions to pay benefits which rise
in value each year by at least 5 per cent or the retail prices index,
whichever is lower.
To introduce age-related rebates of National Insurance contributions for
those with personal pensions or who are members of employer-sponsored
Contracted Out Money Purchase Schemes.
This is intended to discourage those who opt out at a young age, when the
value of the flat-rate rebate is highest, from going back in when they are
older.
To give greater flexibility in converting pension investments into
annuities. This could help those who retire when interest rates are in a
trough - they would otherwise have to buy annuities at the top of the
market, earning lower retirement benefits.
To put in place the recommendations of the white paper on occupational
pension reform. This includes the controversial minimum solvency standard as
well as an equally controversial proposal requiring companies to have
member-elected trustees.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>GBZ  United Kingdom, EC.
</CN>
<XX>
Industries:-
</XX>
<IN>P6371 Pension, Health, and Welfare Funds.
    P9441 Administration of Social and Manpower Programs.
</IN>
<XX>
Types:-
</XX>
<TP>GOVT  Government News.
</TP>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 15
</PAGE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO>FT944-9026</DOCNO>
<PROFILE>_AN-EKQEIADLFT</PROFILE>
<DATE>941117
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  17 NOV 94 / The Queen's Speech: European bill to be given top priority -
Parliamentary timetable
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By KEVIN BROWN, Political Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The government plans to confront its critics - both internal and external -
over the next few weeks by giving parliamentary priority to its European
finance and Jobseeker's Allowance bills.
Senior ministers said the two bills would be introduced quickly in the
Commons, with a third controversial bill to remove a layer of administration
from the National Health Service.
The European bill, which will increase UK contributions to the European
Union, will provide the main battleground between the parties, not least
because of the government's threat to call a general election if it is
amended or defeated.
The bill on the Jobseeker's Allowance, which replaces unemployment benefit,
will face tough opposition from the Labour party, which says that it will
strip 90,000 people of benefits and force means testing on a further
150,000.
The NHS proposals are also guaranteed a stormy passage through parliament
because of strong Labour opposition to the prospect of substantial job
losses and claims that the reforms will damage patient care.
Much of the remainder of the government's programme will be given a fair
wind by the opposition parties, including the bills to reform discipline in
the medical profession and set up a review body to investigate miscarriages
of justice.
The parliamentary business managers have chosen to start two uncontroversial
bills - reforming agricultural land tenure and the Scottish criminal justice
system - in the Lords, where a series of important bills were mauled in the
last session.
The government has yet to work out a timetable for other bills which are
likely to prompt criticism from MPs and peers of all parties. These include:
A hybrid bill to authorise the construction of a high-speed rail link from
London to the Channel tunnel, which will allow opponents of the scheme from
Kent and east London to petition parliament.
A bill to tackle discrimination against the disabled. The bill is unlikely
to satisfy campaigners, who are still angry about the way that Conservative
whips killed a more comprehensive private member's bill in the summer.
Many Conservative MPs and peers were privately sympathetic to the earlier
bill, and the opposition parties may attempt to embarrass the government by
tabling a second private bill, possibly in the Lords.
</TEXT>
