<HEADLINE>
FT  17 NOV 94 / The Queen's Speech: Moves on bias set to anger activists -
Disabled
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE, Social Affairs Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Government attempts to tackle discrimination against disabled people are
likely to inflame rather than satisfy campaigners.
A bill is to be introduced reflecting proposals in 'Disability - On The
Agenda', a government consultation document published in July. This was
produced after a furore in May, when the government blocked a private
member's bill from Mr Roger Berry, a Labour MP, designed to outlaw
discrimination against disabled people.
The consultation document concentrated on employment, access to goods and
services, financial services, building regulations and the establishment of
a new advisory body.
Disability activists regard the document's proposals as inadequate and will
take the same view of a bill based on them.
They are concerned that important areas such as transport and education are
likely to be excluded from the bill's scope, while the suggested new
advisory body would lack legal enforcement powers of bodies such as the
Commission for Racial Equality and the Equal Opportunities Commission.
The government could run into parliamentary pressure to strengthen its bill
if a survey of MPs by the charity Scope - formerly the Spastics Society -
proves correct. This suggests that 25 per cent of Conservative MPs believe
Mr Berry's stronger proposals should be implemented, with 71 per cent of
Conservatives saying they support them in principle but were concerned that
the costs would be too high.
In its opposition to Mr Berry's bill the government costed the extension of
disabled people's rights at Pounds 17bn plus a recurring Pounds 1bn a year.
Disability campaigners say such estimates are unrealistically high.
Lord Ashley, co-chairman of the all-party parliamentary disablement group,
said yesterday that he intended to introduce his own bill in the Lords. The
government's proposals were 'belated, limited and inadequate', he said.
Radar - the Royal Association for Disability and Rehabilitation - said the
consultation document's proposals on which the bill would be based were half
measures. Radar added: 'They will not ensure that disabled people have
equality of opportunity in all aspects of their lives, nor will they give
disabled people the right to legal redress against unfair discrimination.'
Campaigners in the UK are encouraged by an apparent change of attitude
towards the wide-ranging Americans With Disabilities Act in the US.
Although the act was originally opposed by employers because of similar cost
concerns to those advanced in the UK, there is now evidence of greater
acceptance and support. The disability lobby in the UK, however, does not
have the political strength of its US counterpart. Public alarm about
murders and other violent offences committed by people with serious mental
disorders has prompted tighter controls in a mental health bill.
The bill will introduce new powers of supervised discharge from hospital,
and extend from six months to 12 months the period during which released
patients can be recalled.
Mental health charities will oppose the proposals. They say that
better-funded community care is required, rather than changes in the law
that will stigmatise mentally ill people.
</TEXT>
