<HEADLINE>
FT  17 NOV 94 / The Queen's Speech: Critics fear effect of streamlining
proposals - National Health Service
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN PIKE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Organisational change started by the government's 1991 reforms to the
National Health Service will continue with the abolition of health
authorities in their present form.
England's eight surviving regional health authorities will be abolished by
the health authorities bill.
The authorities will be replaced by regional offices of the NHS executive,
which is responsible for the daily running of the service. Although the aim
is to streamline the central structure now that patient services are managed
locally, critics fear the end of regional authorities may increase
accountability problems.
The bill will create about 100 multipurpose local health authorities in
England. These will replace the existing 111 district health authorities -
responsible for purchasing hospital and community services - and 92 family
health service authorities, which handle the family doctor service. The
authorities already work closely together in many parts of the country.
Ministers say the cut in the number of regional authorities and other
administrative changes have already saved Pounds 30m, and they expect
further substantial management savings.
The government intends to tighten sanctions on doctors who underperform with
the medical act (amendment) bill. At present the General Medical Council,
the profession's disciplinary body, can take action only if doctors are
guilty of serious professional misconduct. The bill will extend its
disciplinary powers to those whose performance is consistently poor.
</TEXT>
