<HEADLINE>
FT  17 NOV 94 / The Queen's Speech: Climbdown on full-blown sale - Crown
Agents
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN AUTHERS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The Crown Agents, the government agency responsible for financial,
professional and procurement services in developing countries, is to be
moved into the private sector.
The measure, announced in the Queen's Speech, marks a climbdown from
original plans for full-blown privatisation. Instead, the agency will be
transferred to an independent foundation, limited by guarantee, and with no
government representatives on the board.
Managers of the agency, which plays an important role in implementing the
Overseas Development Administration's bilateral aid programme, welcomed the
move. They believe it will create greater accountability and prove to
clients that it is independent of government pressure to 'buy British'.
The move is not intended to raise money, although it is possible a small
amount will be raised from the repayment of debts owed by the Crown Agents
to the government.
The agency has made payments of about Pounds 20m in capital and interest
since it was established in its present form in 1979, but last year made a
profit of only Pounds 244,000.
The agency employs 800 staff with offices in 38 countries and an annual
turnover of about Pounds 250m, making it one of the world's biggest
purchasing organisations. It receives no regular subsidy and less than 30
per cent of its income is generated from the UK.
Its new structure is similar to that of the Wellcome Foundation, the health
insurance groups PPP and Bupa, the AA and RAC motoring organisations and the
British Standards Institute.
The board will include members who reflect 'the international character of
the agency's work', as well as representatives of aid agencies and the
commercial sector.
The agency's profits will not be distributed but will be reinvested in its
work, which it says has a 'social purpose'.
</TEXT>
