<HEADLINE>
FT  17 NOV 94 / The Queen's Speech: Pollution agency wins approval -
Environment
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By BRONWEN MADDOX
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The long-awaited Environment Agency to regulate pollution has finally won
the go-ahead with the inclusion of the environment agencies bill in the
Queen's Speech yesterday.
The agency, seen by ministers as a 'one-stop shop' for pollution regulation,
will merge Her Majesty's Pollution Inspectorate, the National Rivers
Authority and the waste regulation functions of local authorities. Mr John
Gummer, environment secretary, has said the integration will result in a
leaner, fitter, 'more together' regulator.
The government also made clear yesterday that it was determined to push
ahead with controversial schemes to raise the proportion of waste packaging
which is recovered or recycled. Further legislation to encourage
industry-led recycling programmes could follow, it said.
Manufacturers and retailers have been concerned that increasing the amount
of recycling, a UK obligation under the European Union packaging directive,
could add Pounds 100m to costs at some point along the chain between
production and point of sale, and would increase the cost of the weekly
shopping basket.
The environment agencies bill will also establish a Scottish Environment
Protection Agency and include measures to set up new independent authorities
for the 10 national parks in England and Wales.
Environmental pressure groups yesterday greeted the announcement warily.
Many, such as Greenpeace, the Royal Society for the Protection of Birds and
Friends of the Earth, have criticised the proposals on the grounds that the
new agency would be too soft on industry.
Friends of the Earth said yesterday that after the creation of the agency it
would be less easy to pursue court cases against the government. At present
ministers have a 'duty to further nature conservation', but the draft bill
says instead that they must 'have regard to the desirability of conserving
and enhancing natural beauty', the group said.
Debate on the structure of the bill has also provoked argument between the
present pollution regulators. Officials from the pollution inspectorate and
local authorities have been concerned that the agency would be dominated by
the NRA, which employs thousands of people to monitor the state of rivers,
separate from its regulatory role.
</TEXT>
