<HEADLINE>
FT  17 NOV 94 / Lloyd's may face fresh Pounds 1bn claim
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RALPH ATKINS, Insurance Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The latest group of Lloyd's of London members to launch legal proceedings in
an attempt to win compensation for losses yesterday said their total claims
could exceed Pounds 1bn.
The Sturge Names Action Group, which represents more than 3,000 Names -
individuals whose assets have traditionally supported the insurance market -
said it hoped to raise about Pounds 5m from members for its fighting fund
and to begin issuing writs in January.
Syndicates run by Sturge managing agents were among the worst-affected by
Lloyd's recent problems, including heavy US asbestosis and pollution claims.
But the action group acknowledged that the pool of funds available to meet
damages won by any Lloyd's Name was limited and could be exhausted by cases
further ahead in the legislative queue. It is likely to be more than 18
months before any Sturge case reaches court.
Mr John Rew, action group chairman, hinted that the group was hoping for a
fresh attempt by Lloyd's at an out-of-court deal. Many Names believe that if
another attempt is made at a settlement those pursuing legal action would
fare better that those who are not.
The action group said total losses on the relevant Sturge syndicates in 1990
and 1991, the latest years to be reported, had reached Pounds 747m but might
exceed Pounds 1bn.
The action group is focusing initially on claiming damages for losses
incurred by syndicate 210, run by one of the Sturge managing agencies, which
are subsidiaries of Sturge Holdings. Mr David Coleridge, chairman of Sturge
Holdings, is a former chairman of Lloyd's.
The action group's case is that a reinsurance policy taken out by the
syndicate in the 1970s to provide protection against 'long-tail' liabilities
 -those which can take many years to produce claims - should not have been
commuted in 1991. The action group says that removing the reinsurance cover
resulted in Names losing at least Pounds 100m.
The group said it planned legal action against Sturge managing agencies,
agencies which placed members on Sturge syndicates, and Neville Russell,
Sturge's auditors.
</TEXT>
