<HEADLINE>
FT  17 NOV 94 / Unexpected debt repayment reduces PSBR to Pounds 19.2bn
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER NORMAN, Economics Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Mr Kenneth Clarke's Budget planning was given a boost yesterday when the
government announced an unexpected repayment of debt in October instead of
the usual budget deficit.
With the chancellor putting the final touches to his November 29 Budget, the
Treasury and Central Statistical Office announced a public sector debt
repayment of Pounds 558m last month, compared with City expectations of a
public-sector borrowing requirement of about Pounds 1.1bn and September's
deficit of Pounds 4.09bn.
The October repayment was the first monthly budget surplus since January and
reduced the cumulative PSBR to Pounds 19.2bn for the first seven months of
the 1994-95 financial year from Pounds 19.7bn in the first six months.
The deficit for April to October was Pounds 7.2bn less than the Pounds
26.4bn recorded in the first seven months of the past financial year and
appears to leave the government well on course to undershoot the Treasury's
summer forecast of Pounds 36.1bn for the PSBR in 1994-95.
The local authorities' borrowing requirement was estimated at close to zero
last month. In the first seven months local authorities paid back about
Pounds 800m of debt after net repayments of Pounds 1.8bn in the same period
last year.
Government receipts were swollen by Pounds 1.47bn of privatisation proceeds
in October, mainly from the third tranche of the BT share sale.
Privatisation proceeds totalled Pounds 3.8bn in the April-to-October period
compared with Pounds 3.5bn at the same stage last year.
Receipts in October were also boosted by unexpectedly strong inflows of
corporation tax. These jumped to Pounds 5.51bn last month from Pounds 3.59bn
in October last year and Pounds 4.08bn in October 1992, reflecting the
beneficial impact of economic recovery on company profits.
Total cash receipts were Pounds 20.3bn last month. They rose 8.5 per cent to
Pounds 126.6bn in the first seven months of 1994-95 compared with the same
1993-94 period. Cash outlays were Pounds 20.2bn last month. The Pounds
148.1bn spending total in the first seven months was only 2 per cent higher
than in April to October last year.
Inland Revenue receipts in the seven months were 14 per cent higher than
last year, while those of Customs and Excise were up 9.5 per cent and social
security contributions were 11 per cent higher.
On the spending side, net departmental outlays were up about 1.5 per cent in
the seven months. According to Mr Kevin Darlington and Ms Helen MacFarlane,
economists at brokers Hoare Govett, this low growth, reflecting low
inflation and falling unemployment, should enable Mr Clarke to cut about
Pounds 5bn from spending plans for this year.
Analysts warned, however, against expectations of such a sharp downward
revision of this year's PSBR forecast in the Budget. Government spending
tends to gather pace as the financial year progresses. Although corporation
tax inflows are strong, lower-than-expected inflation has depressed receipts
from income tax and value added tax receipts below government expectations.
This month's Treasury survey of independent forecasts showed an average
expectation that the 1994-95 PSBR will be Pounds 32.6bn, falling to Pounds
24bn in 1995-96.
</TEXT>
