<HEADLINE>
FT  17 NOV 94 / City bankers feel squeeze, not chop: Big job cuts are rare
as yet
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NICHOLAS DENTON and JOHN GAPPER
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
Employees at City merchant and investment banks may be nervously awaiting
redundancy notices as their organisations approach the end of their
financial years and begin budgeting for the next.
But the most stringent cuts so far have been not of jobs, but of expenses -
the main casualties of austerity are taxi-drivers, caterers and newspaper
publishers.
Lehman Brothers, the US investment bank, has put cost control policy into
action with a ban on the use of taxis at the company's expense before 9pm.
Employees' newspaper subscriptions are examined for duplication and, if
necessary, ended.
Entertainment, as always, is a target. Gifts distributed at the firm's
receptions are strictly for guests: Lehman staff may not now help
themselves. Corporate events should be centred on clients as much as
possible. 'There should be no departmental lunches on the firm just because
there is not much going on,' said a Lehman executive.
The firm's impressively named European Expense Advisory Committee is
inspiring and co-ordinating belt-tightening. Lehman defended using senior
managers' time in identifying small cost savings: 'It all adds up,' it said.
Lehman, although rumoured to be preparing swingeing redundancies, says
departures are in single figures and the reason for them is substandard
performance.
Other US investment banks hit by the downturn in world bond markets have
been cutting more radically. Goldman Sachs this week completed a round of 90
redundancies - nearly 5 per cent of its European headcount.
SG Warburg, the UK investment bank which last week reported sharply lower
interim profits, has made 10 people redundant. NatWest Markets has pulled
out of several corporate bond markets and lowered staffing by 12 as a
result.
These disclosures have fuelled anxiety among City employees, but they do not
yet represent the massacre portrayed by the rumour-mill and the headlines.
Goldman Sachs has made the deepest cuts so far but the firm's London
headcount has been rising this year and will remain higher than in January
even after the redundancies.
SG Warburg describes its policy as a 'freeze' at the staffing level of
September 30. 'It would be foolish to get involved in panic measures which
would affect the fabric of the business,' it said.
Hambros, which yesterday reported a sharp fall in interim profits, set
itself against staff cuts in the bond division which suffered most from
adverse market conditions this year.
'If anything, we are expanding it,' said Sir Chips Keswick, deputy chairman.
'It is a core business and we have no intention of leaving it.'
Remuneration is another matter. Goldman Sachs expects to inform employees
about their bonuses in a few days. The average is expected to plummet from
last year and Goldman, as the first investment bank to decide, puts down a
benchmark.
There may be more sackings to come, or to come to light. Visible
redundancies can undermine client confidence. Investment banks privately
admit that they, or at least their competitors, fudge redundancies by
putting them under the heading of quality control. In general, City firms
fervently deny any intention to embark on mass dismissals until they
actually do so.
</TEXT>
