<HEADLINE>
FT  17 NOV 94 / Demolition plan for Wembley
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANTONY THORNCROFT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
English Heritage, the guardian of historic sites, yesterday gave tentative
permission for the demolition of Wembley Stadium, a Grade II listed
building, but found fault with plans to modernise it.
It said: 'The international standing of Wembley demands a much more
imaginative approach than shown in this scheme.' Wembley's distinctive twin
towers and grand entrance block must be retained, it added.
The application to renovate the London stadium came from the Genesis
Corporation, which last month approached Wembley plc, the site's owner, with
an investment offer which was rejected. Genesis then approached the London
Borough of Brent, which consulted English Heritage about the redevelopment
plans.
Wembley plc, which has debts of Pounds 150m, yesterday 'noted with great
interest' the decision of English Heritage.
English Heritage is keen to see the stadium modernised. It said: 'The
redevelopment would bring Wembley up to Olympic standard, with increased
seating capacity and modern facilities.
'Whilst we therefore would not be minded to authorise the grant of listed
building consent for the proposals as they stand, we hope that the
applicants will reconsider their scheme in the light of our comments and put
forward what might be considered a more radical scheme which we could
unequivocally support.'
</TEXT>
