<HEADLINE>
FT  17 NOV 94 / Labour pulls rug from under Reynolds: A new coalition is
possible in theory but general elections are the more likely option
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN MURRAY BROWN
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   DUBLIN
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
The dramatic events yesterday in the Dail, the Irish parliament, leave
Ireland facing a period of political uncertainty and cast new doubt over the
future of the Northern Ireland peace process.
The resignation of Mr Dick Spring, the deputy prime minister and Labour
party leader, and his fellow ministers brings the prospect of early general
elections and the break-up of the 22-month-old Fianna Fail-led government.
It will be viewed in London, in particular, with deep concern.
What is all the more surprising is that this is a government with the
largest majority in the history of the Irish Republic, a track record of
fiscal and monetary rectitude and the fastest economic growth record of any
member of the European Union.
What is more, the coalition, largely through the determination of Mr Albert
Reynolds, the prime minister, has achieved what he rightly claims is the
'biggest breakthrough in Northern Ireland in 25 years' in helping to secure
the IRA's ceasefire.
With the Dail still in a state of shock, attention will shift today to
President Mary Robinson's residence in Phoenix Park.
The political odds are that Mrs Robinson, who made history as the country's
first woman president, will make history again by refusing to grant Mr
Reynolds a dissolution of parliament. Earlier this week she sought
consultations with the head of the Bar Council. Under the constitution the
president can refuse to dissolve the Dail if a prime minister has ceased to
retain majority support. That palpably has now been demonstrated.
The current thinking is that President Robinson would give the parties in
parliament a fixed period, probably a week, to form a new coalition. If
unsuccessful, the government would be forced to go to the country.
As far as the peace process is concerned, all parties, as Sir Patrick
Mayhew, the UK's Northern Ireland secretary, repeated on Tuesday, are
publicly committed to the search for peace as outlined by both governments
in the Joint Declaration.
However, while the hatching of a new government continues, officials say the
negotiations on the framework document to provide a durable peace will have
to be put on hold. In such a limbo, there are growing doubts whether London
will decide to bring Sinn Fein, the IRA's political wing, into exploratory
discussions by Christmas.
If elections turn out to be unavoidable, it could be well into the new year
before a new administration is in a position to pick up the negotiating
baton on the Northern Ireland peace process.
Irish politics it seems has a cruel way of repeating itself. Just two years
ago an earlier coalition between Fianna Fail and the Progressive Democrats
broke up, on that occasion over allegations relating to the Beef Tribunal,
the investigation into the misuse of official export credits.
The row between Mr Reynolds and Mr Des O'Malley, the then PD leader, forced
an early general election. It seems acutely ironic that the Labour party's
strong showing in that election, securing 33 seats, was due directly to the
anti-Fianna Fail vote. That the party ended up in coalition with Fianna
Fail, the first such coalition in Irish political history, was never
envisaged.
If Mr Reynolds survived that row, it is inconceivable he can survive the
current attacks. Already yesterday there were calls for his resignation.
Last night the name being widely canvassed to replace him was the finance
minister, Mr Bertie Ahern - ironically the only minister who remained on the
front benches together with his party leader throughout his political
ordeal.
In the Dail, party managers were last night weighing up the options. For
Fianna Fail, even with a new leader, a general election would be the only
way back. For Labour, the calculation seems more complicated.
One choice is to try to cobble together a coalition with Fine Gael and one
or other of the Democratic Left or the Progressive Democrats. Current
parliamentary strengths would give a narrow arithmetic majority in the
166-seat legislature.
The possibility is discounted by some politicians who point to Mr Spring's
frosty relations with Mr John Bruton, the Fine Gael leader. Even at the
height of his indictment of Mr Reynolds, the Labour leader could not resist
scoring a few points at Mr Bruton's expense.
The other consideration for Mr Spring is that Labour held six cabinet
portfolios in the last government. It is hard to envisage that a rainbow
coalition would provide the party with so much visibility.
And in bringing the crisis to a head, Mr Spring has almost certainly counted
on the prospect of early polls, believing that Labour's performance and the
issue of public accountability would play out well for the party in a
general election.
</TEXT>
