<HEADLINE>
FT  17 NOV 94 / French attack US policy on Bosnia: Row highlights drifting
apart of US and its European allies
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LIONEL BARBER and BRUCE CLARK, Diplomatic Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   STRASBOURG, LONDON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
France yesterday stepped up its criticism of US policy in Bosnia, amid a
further cooling of transatlantic relations because of differences over the
war in former Yugoslavia.
At a Nato meeting in Brussels, the US failed to convince its European allies
to take immediate action over the Bosnian enclave of Bihac, where Serb
forces were closing in.
Mr Alain Juppe, French foreign minister, said the US withdrawal from
enforcing the arms embargo against Bosnia amounted to favouring those who
wanted war against those who wanted peace.
Mr Francois Leotard, the defence minister, threatened to withdraw French
troops from Bosnia in the event of 'one more step' in the wrong direction.
Mr Juppe will tomorrow host a meeting with Mr Douglas Hurd and Mr Andrei
Kozyrev, his counterparts from the UK and Russia, with the Bosnian crisis -
and their common disappointment with US policy - high on the agenda.
Officials from several European countries said they were concerned by
reports of covert US military aid to Bosnian Moslems and Croats, aimed at
helping them to fight together against the Serbs. This aid is reported to
include training and the construction of small airfields.
However, the battered five-nation contact group on Bosnia - US, Russia,
Britain, France and Germany - has scheduled a ministerial meeting for
December 2, in a sign that efforts to harmonise policy will continue.
Transatlantic differences over Bosnia and other issues have already prompted
some public soul-searching by policy-makers and scholars on how the
US-European relationship can be shored up.
Mr Malcolm Rifkind, the UK defence secretary, has suggested that increased
exchanges between civil servants, businessmen and scholars could help
maintain an 'Atlantic community' based on shared values.
A report reflecting the views of businessmen and politicians on both sides
of the Atlantic called this week for a new US-European treaty. It says the
Europeans underestimate the degree to which US and European foreign policy
interests diverge in the absence of a Soviet threat. The report sees a risk
of cleavage as Americans tilt away from Europe to the fast-growing economies
in Latin America and the Pacific, and as both allies become preoccupied with
internal renewal and economic competition.
Though not in any immediate peril, 'the transatlantic relationship founded
primarily on the (Nato) alliance is adrift,' concludes the study by
Transatlantic Policy Network.
The report recommends three steps:
The transformation of the present Transatlantic Declaration into an economic
and political treaty between the EU and US aimed at creating a 'North
Atlantic Free Trade Area'.
Reforming Nato around a partnership between the US and a European defence
pillar. Though the authors suggest further integrating defence and military
procurement in Europe, they found 'no firm foundation' for a coherent
European approach on security matters.
Uniting the annual Nato summit and the biennial US-EU meetings. The aim is
to exploit the Clinton administration's shift toward strengthening the
European defence pillar within Nato.
Toward Transatlantic Partnership - a European Strategy: TPN, Rue Froissart,
1040 Brussels.
</TEXT>
<XX>
Countries:-
</XX>
<CN>FRZ  France, EC.
    USZ  United States of America.
    BAZ  Bosnia-Hercegovina, East Europe.
</CN>
<XX>
