<HEADLINE>
FT  17 NOV 94 / Brussels payments and welfare to fore in government
programme
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IVOR OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
The measure authorising the increase in the UK's payments to the European
Union and the normal finance bill implementing the Budget to be introduced
on November 29 will dominate the early stages of the new parliamentary
session, Ivor Owen writes.
Social welfare legislation, including the measure to equalise the state
pension age at 65 for men and women by 2020, will also figure prominently in
the programme.
The jobseekers' allowance bill will replace unemployment benefits and income
support. The Crown Agents, a leading international supplier of procurement,
financial management and technical services, features in a restricted
privatisation programme.  This includes increased competition in the gas
industry by allowing domestic customers to choose their supplier, and
transferring the commercial activities of the Atomic Energy Authority to the
private sector.
A hybrid bill will seek authority for the construction and operation by the
private sector of a high-speed rail link between London and the Channel
tunnel.
Other measures include: a bill to save administrative costs in the National
Health Service; an agricultural tenancies bill to make tenanted land more
readily available; a bill setting up an independent body to investigate
alleged miscarriages of justice; and an environment agencies bill to
establish environment protection agencies.
</TEXT>
