<DATE>941117
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  17 NOV 94 / RJB forecasts profits of Pounds 220m if it buys English coal
regions
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHAEL SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
RJB Mining, the coal company, is telling potential investors it can make
annual pre-tax profits of Pounds 220m by the turn of the century from the
English regions of British Coal which it is negotiating to buy from the
government.
In one of the boldest and most controversial fund-raising exercises in
recent times on the London Stock Exchange, RJB aims to raise Pounds 425m in
a share issue and Pounds 628m as debt.
In private City presentations, RJB and its adviser, Barclays de Zoete Wedd,
indicate that they believe the debt can be cleared by 1998 when existing
electricity contracts end.
RJB, which put in an offer of Pounds 914m to win the government's backing as
preferred bidder for the regions, forecasts annual pre-tax profits of Pounds
220m on turnover of Pounds 1.24bn in 1999. Profits before then will be
Pounds 116m in 1995, Pounds 188m in 1996, Pounds 211m in 1997 and Pounds
186m in 1998.
The amount of money RJB, capitalised at Pounds 157m, needs to raise means
that investors will study its projections closely. Many executives in the
electricity and coal industries believe the company, which bid up to 50 per
cent more than its nearest rival, is taking a highly optimistic view of
markets.
RJB will win the regions if it can raise the money and agree final terms
with the government.
RJB, which yesterday refused to comment, says in its presentation it expects
to sell about 34m tonnes of coal from those regions and sell them at an
average of Pounds 1.32 a gigajoule at today's prices.
Some analysts believe sales around the mid-20m tonne mark are more
realistic. The generators, to which most of the coal will be sold, are
thought to want to buy coal for nearer Pounds 1 a gigajoule and are prepared
to import rather than pay what they believe to be excessive UK prices.
Among other key aspects of the presentation, RJB says:
Costs per tonne can be cut by at least 10 per cent, partly through
streamlining colliery management and increasing equipment utilisation.
The English electricity supply market will require 27.1m-43m tonnes a year
by 1999. Of the Pounds 628m of borrowing, Pounds 528m will be bank debt and
Pounds 100m corporate bonds.
Net assets of the regions are Pounds 902m and projected operating cash flow
over five years is Pounds 1.35bn.
Expected dividend yield is 4.5 per cent initially. Some 95 per cent of
shares will be placed with institutions, with 5 per cent set aside for an
offer for sale, but this could rise to 15 per cent if there is demand.
Details, Page 24
</TEXT>
